[[File:Chagu Chagu Umako Festival circa 1934.jpg|thumb|right|photo of the ''Chagu Chagu Umakko'' circa 1934]] {{nihongo|'''Chagu Chagu Umakko'''|チャグチャグ馬コ}} is a horse [[Japanese festival|festival]] in [[Iwate Prefecture]], [[Japan]]. Held on the second Saturday in June, approximately one hundred horses with colourful fittings and bells parade between Sozen [[Shrine]] in [[Takizawa, Iwate|Takizawa]] and [[Morioka]] [[Hachiman shrine|Hachiman-gū]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.japan-iwate.info/app/location_detail.php?lid=51 |title=Chagu Chagu Umakko Festival (Takizawa Village; Morioka City) |publisher=[[Iwate Prefecture]] |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> The term ''chagu-chagu'' is an [[onomatopoeic]] expression for the sound made by the horses' bells.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jnto.go.jp/eng/indepth/history/traditionalevents/a30_fes_chagu.html |title=Chagu Chagu Umako Horse Festival |publisher=[[Japan National Tourism Organization]] |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> In 1978 the festival was recorded as an [[Intangible Folk Cultural Property]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bunka.go.jp/bsys/maindetails.asp?register_id=312&item_id=198 |title=Database of National Cultural Properties |publisher=[[Agency for Cultural Affairs]] |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> In 1996 the sound of the bells of the Chagu Chagu Umakko was selected by the [[Ministry of the Environment (Japan)|Ministry of the Environment]] as one of the [[100 Soundscapes of Japan]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.env.go.jp/air/life/oto/ |title=北海道・東北 - チャグチャグ馬コの鈴の音 |publisher=[[Ministry of the Environment (Japan)|Ministry of the Environment]] |accessdate=18 April 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120608002719/http://www.env.go.jp/air/life/oto/ |archivedate=8 June 2012 |df= }}</ref>
