[[File:Ethcofcerm.jpg|thumb|200px|An [[Ethiopia]]n woman roasting coffee at a traditional ceremony.]] A '''coffee ceremony''' ({{lang-am|ቡና ማፍላት|bunna maflat}}) is a ritualized form of making and drinking [[coffee]]. The coffee ceremony was first practiced in Ethiopia and Eritrea. There is a routine of serving coffee on a daily basis, mainly for the purpose of getting together with relatives, neighbors, or other visitors. If coffee is politely declined, then [[tea]] (''Chai'') will most likely be served.
Loose [[Poaceae|grass]] is spread on the floor where the coffee ceremony is held, often decorated with small yellow flowers. [[Asteraceae|Composite]] flowers are sometimes used, especially around the celebration of [[Meskel]].
==Brewing== [[File:Coffee ceremony.jpg|thumb|200px|An [[Eritrea]]n woman pouring traditionally brewed coffee into [[finjal]] from a [[jebena]].]] The ceremony is typically performed by the woman of the household and is considered an honor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://drinks.seriouseats.com/2011/05/coffee-traditions-the-ethiopian-coffee-ceremony.html|title=Coffee Traditions: Ethiopian Coffee Ceremony|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161113114621/http://drinks.seriouseats.com/2011/05/coffee-traditions-the-ethiopian-coffee-ceremony.html|archivedate=2016-11-13|df=}}</ref> The coffee is brewed by first roasting the green coffee beans over an open flame in a pan .<ref name="laweekly" /><ref name="epicurean" /> This is followed by the grinding of the beans, traditionally in a [[wooden]] [[mortar and pestle]].<ref name="epicurean" /> The coffee grounds are then put into a special vessel which contain boiled water and will be left on an open flame a couple of minutes until it is well mixed with the hot water.<ref name="laweekly">{{cite web|url=http://www.laweekly.com/restaurants/experience-a-true-ethiopian-coffee-ceremony-in-las-little-ethiopia-6445661|title=Experience a True Ethiopian Coffee Ceremony in L.A.'s Little Ethiopia|last1=Tavitian|first1=Maral|date=January 5, 2016|access-date=November 11, 2016|website=LA Weekly|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161112040823/http://www.laweekly.com/restaurants/experience-a-true-ethiopian-coffee-ceremony-in-las-little-ethiopia-6445661|archivedate=November 12, 2016|df=}}</ref> After grinding, the coffee is put through a sieve several times.<ref name="epicurean" /> The boiling pot ([[jebena]]) is usually made of [[pottery]] and has a spherical base, a [[neck]] and pouring spout, and a handle where the neck connects with the base.<ref name="epicurean" /> The jebena also has a straw lid.<ref name="epicurean" />
==Serving== [[File:Himbasha.jpg|thumb|right|120px|[[Himbasha|Ambasha]] is sometimes used as snack during the ceremonies]] The host pours the coffee for all participants by moving the tilted boiling pot over a tray with small, handleless cups from a height of one foot without stop until each cup is full.<ref name="epicurean" /> The grounds are brewed three times: the first round of coffee is called ''awel'' in [[Tigrinya language|Tigrinya]], the second ''kale'i'' and the third ''baraka'' ('to be blessed').<ref name="coffeeland">{{cite web|url=http://www.afar.com/magazine/coffeeland|title=Coffeland|magazine=Afar|last1=Farley|first1=David|date=April 8, 2013|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161113042118/http://www.afar.com/magazine/coffeeland|archivedate=November 13, 2016|df=}}</ref> The coffee ceremony may also include burning of various traditional [[incense]].<ref name="coffeeland" /> People add sugar to their coffee, or in the countryside, sometimes salt or traditional butter (see ''[[niter kibbeh]]'').<ref name="epicurean" /> The beverage is accompanied by a small snack such as popcorn, peanuts or [[himbasha]] (also called ''ambasha'').<ref name="epicurean">{{cite web|url=http://www.epicurean.com/articles/ethiopian-coffee-ceremony.html|title=Ethiopian Coffee Ceremony|last1=Doyle|first1=Emily|website=Epicurian.com|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091003021517/http://www.epicurean.com/articles/ethiopian-coffee-ceremony.html|archivedate=2009-10-03|df=}}</ref>
